<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="329" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="17.[159,772,1207,2019]" box="[159,298,1207,1233]" pageId="17" pageNumber="329">
<emphasis box="[159,298,1207,1233]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="329">Description</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[159,772,1207,2019]" lastBlockId="17.[816,1429,220,347]" pageId="17" pageNumber="329">
A small, nondescript, species with a very short forearm length (
<quantity box="[366,483,1275,1301]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.61" pageId="17" pageNumber="329" unit="mm" value="26.1">26.1 mm</quantity>
) (
<tableCitation box="[515,615,1275,1301]" captionStart="TABLE" captionStartId="7.[159,172,220,241]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="TABLE 2. External measurements (mm) and bacular length (mm) of 14 bat species recently collected at Lekoumou, Congo.Acronyms explained in the Materials and Methods section include means, ranges, and, where relevant, standard deviations. Numbers in parentheses refer to sample size where they differ from those stated in column 2" httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/5FAA6645FF93C07DFF03FF23FC6EFEEE" pageId="17" pageNumber="329" tableUuid="5FAA6645FF93C07DFF03FF23FC6EFEEE">Table 2</tableCitation>
). The interfemoral and wing membranes are uniformly dark; the pelage is also uniformly dark on the back and buff-brown on the belly. The muzzle is thick and broadly rounded. In each ear, the tragus has a very slightly concave anterior border, a rounded tip, a smoothly rounded posterior border and a well developed basal lobule (
<figureCitation box="[430,529,1514,1540]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="11.[159,172,1911,1932]" captionTargetBox="[287,1299,1270,1885]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[211,1406,1263,1892]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIG. 8. Right tragus of (A): Glauconycteris alboguttata, HZM.1.40172, ♀; (B): G. beatrix, HZM.1.40181, ♀; (C): Hypsugo crassulus, HZM.1.40190, ♂; (D): Neoromicia brunnea, HZM.1.40191, ♂; (E): N. nana, HZM.321.40186, ♂; (F): N. tenuipinnis, HZM.7.40170, ♀; (G): Pipistrellus nanulus, HZM.1.40189, ♂; (H): Mimetillus moloneyi, HZM.10.40177, ♂; (I): Miniopterus inflatus, HZM.19.40182, ♂. Scale = 2 mm" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3943579" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3943579/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="329">Fig. 8G</figureCitation>
). The skull is short (
<collectionCode box="[167,226,1548,1574]" pageId="17" pageNumber="329">GTL</collectionCode>
= 
<quantity box="[254,379,1548,1574]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.199" pageId="17" pageNumber="329" unit="mm" value="11.99">11.99 mm</quantity>
) (
<tableCitation box="[407,501,1548,1574]" captionStart="TABLE" captionStartId="8.[99,112,725,746]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="TABLE 3. Cranial and dental measurements (mm) of 14 bat species recently collected at Lekoumou, Congo.Acronyms explained in the Materials and Methods section include means, ranges, and, where relevant,standard deviations. Numbers in parentheses refer to sample size where they differ from those stated in column 2" httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/5FAA6645FF9CC072FFFFFD2AFAA7FCC7" pageId="17" pageNumber="329" tableUuid="5FAA6645FF9CC072FFFFFD2AFAA7FCC7">Table 3</tableCitation>
), the rostrum is short and the braincase is low (
<figureCitation box="[464,573,1583,1609]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="14.[159,172,1911,1932]" captionTargetBox="[344,1217,713,1874]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[304,1284,688,1902]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIG. 10. Skulls of three small vespertilionids, including lateral view of right upper incisors and occlusal view of left mandibular dentition (left) and left maxillary dentition (right) of (A): Hypsugo crassulus, HZM.1.40190, ♂; (B): Mimetillus moloneyi, HZM.10.40177, ♂ and (C) Pipistrellus nanulus, HZM.1.40189, ♂. Scales for skulls and occlusal views of toothrows (left and right) = 2 mm; scale for upper incisors (centre) = 1 mm" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3943583" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3943583/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="329">Fig. 10C</figureCitation>
). The first upper incisor (I 
<superScript attach="right" box="[270,280,1612,1630]" fontSize="8" pageId="17" pageNumber="329">2</superScript>
) is strongly bicuspid; the second (I 
<superScript attach="right" box="[720,730,1612,1630]" fontSize="8" pageId="17" pageNumber="329">3</superScript>
) is unicuspid but with a well developed cingulum, it attains two-thirds the height of the secondary cusp of I 
<superScript attach="left" box="[207,217,1715,1733]" fontSize="8" pageId="17" pageNumber="329">2</superScript>
(
<figureCitation box="[239,354,1719,1745]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="14.[159,172,1911,1932]" captionTargetBox="[344,1217,713,1874]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[304,1284,688,1902]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIG. 10. Skulls of three small vespertilionids, including lateral view of right upper incisors and occlusal view of left mandibular dentition (left) and left maxillary dentition (right) of (A): Hypsugo crassulus, HZM.1.40190, ♂; (B): Mimetillus moloneyi, HZM.10.40177, ♂ and (C) Pipistrellus nanulus, HZM.1.40189, ♂. Scales for skulls and occlusal views of toothrows (left and right) = 2 mm; scale for upper incisors (centre) = 1 mm" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3943583" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3943583/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="329">Fig. 10C</figureCitation>
). The small, first upper premolar (P 
<superScript attach="left" box="[185,195,1749,1767]" fontSize="8" pageId="17" pageNumber="329">2</superScript>
) is comparatively well developed and is slightly displaced internally; the canine and second premolar (P 
<superScript attach="left" box="[262,272,1817,1835]" fontSize="8" pageId="17" pageNumber="329">4</superScript>
) are 
<taxonomicName box="[337,374,1822,1848]" class="Not" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" pageId="17" pageNumber="340" phylum="Myzozoa" rank="class">not</taxonomicName>
in contact (
<figureCitation box="[518,628,1822,1848]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="14.[159,172,1911,1932]" captionTargetBox="[344,1217,713,1874]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[304,1284,688,1902]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIG. 10. Skulls of three small vespertilionids, including lateral view of right upper incisors and occlusal view of left mandibular dentition (left) and left maxillary dentition (right) of (A): Hypsugo crassulus, HZM.1.40190, ♂; (B): Mimetillus moloneyi, HZM.10.40177, ♂ and (C) Pipistrellus nanulus, HZM.1.40189, ♂. Scales for skulls and occlusal views of toothrows (left and right) = 2 mm; scale for upper incisors (centre) = 1 mm" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3943583" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3943583/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="329">Fig. 10C</figureCitation>
). The lower canine has a small but well-developed cusp on the anterior cingulum. The first lower premolar (P 
<subScript attach="left" box="[751,761,1905,1923]" fontSize="8" pageId="17" pageNumber="329">2</subScript>
) is about equal in crown area and two-thirds the height of the second (P 
<subScript attach="left" box="[441,451,1973,1991]" fontSize="8" pageId="17" pageNumber="329">4</subScript>
) (
<figureCitation box="[480,591,1958,1984]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="14.[159,172,1911,1932]" captionTargetBox="[344,1217,713,1874]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[304,1284,688,1902]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIG. 10. Skulls of three small vespertilionids, including lateral view of right upper incisors and occlusal view of left mandibular dentition (left) and left maxillary dentition (right) of (A): Hypsugo crassulus, HZM.1.40190, ♂; (B): Mimetillus moloneyi, HZM.10.40177, ♂ and (C) Pipistrellus nanulus, HZM.1.40189, ♂. Scales for skulls and occlusal views of toothrows (left and right) = 2 mm; scale for upper incisors (centre) = 1 mm" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3943583" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3943583/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="329">Fig. 10C</figureCitation>
). The baculum is long, with a bifid tip, a straight shaft and two, relatively ill-defined, basal lobules (
<figureCitation box="[1293,1414,220,246]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="15.[159,172,710,731]" captionTargetBox="[329,1234,229,686]" captionTargetId="figure@15.[313,1265,219,692]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIG. 11. Bacula of four pipistrelles. (A): Hypsugo crassulus, HZM.1.40190; (B): Neoromicia brunnea, HZM.1.40191; (C): N. nana, HZM.321.40186; and (D): Pipistrellus nanulus, HZM.1.40189. Scale = 1 mm" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3943585" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3943585/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="329">Fig. 11D</figureCitation>
); this compares well with the baculum of the 
<typeStatus pageId="17" pageNumber="329">holotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1904" box="[924,1017,287,313]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Pipistrellus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="329" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="nanulus">
<emphasis box="[924,1017,287,313]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="329">nanulus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
illustrated in 
<bibRefCitation author="Hill and Harrison" firstAuthor="Hill" pageId="17" pageNumber="329" pagination="225 - 305" refId="ref14024" refString="HILL, J. E., and D. L. HARRISON. 1987. The baculum in the Vespertilioninae (Chiroptera: Vespertilionidae) with a systematic review, a synopsis of Pipistrellus and Eptesicus, and the description of a new genus and subgenus. Bulletin of the British Museum (Natural History), Zoology, 52: 225 - 305." type="journal article" year="1987">Hill and Harrison (1987</bibRefCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[900,1013,321,347]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="10.[159,172,1966,1987]" captionTargetBox="[364,1229,1530,1948]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[322,1290,1525,1958]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIG. 7. Nycteris hispida, HZM.52.40188. (A): Anterior, left mandible; (B): left, upper incisors and canine; (C): right tragus; (D): baculum (dorsal view [left] and lateral view [right]). Scales for A, B, and D = 1 mm; scale for C = 2 mm" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3943577" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3943577/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="329">Figure 7f</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="329" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="17.[816,1429,388,515]" box="[816,1014,388,414]" pageId="17" pageNumber="329">
